### Describe the bug

I want to model bind all parameters (body, path, query, header, custom model bound) into one flat class.  Simple reduced example:  
```
public record ArtistRequestFlat
{
    [FromBody]
    public string? Name { get; init; }

    [FromBody]
    public string? StageName { get; init; }

    [FromHeader(Name = "Accept-Language")]
    public List<string> PreferredLanguages { get; init; }

    [FromQuery]
    public string? SelectedLanguage { get; init; }
}
```
Using this model in a controller method...
```
[Route("one-class")]
[HttpPost
public ActionResult<ArtistRequest> PostOneClass(ArtistRequest artistRequest)
{
    return Ok(artistRequest);
}
```
...doesn't fill the query and header parameter, because even there is no explicit `[FromBody]` before the method parameter it is added by ApiExplorer by convention and then everything is treated as from body. It doesn't make sense by the interface and the result is not expected, but this is how it is documented. 

The stated solution is to use an (unintuitive) `[FromQuery]` attribute:
```
[Route("one-class-fromquery")]
[HttpPost]
public ActionResult<ArtistRequest> PostOneClassFromQuery([FromQuery] ArtistRequest artistRequest)
{
    return Ok(artistRequest);
}
```
This still doesn't work. It produces an error:
```
{
    "type": "https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7231#section-6.5.1",
    "title": "One or more validation errors occurred.",
    "status": 400,
    "traceId": "00-466102e0747df4fc2cc15e4d265456f2-813ed2b8da192054-00",
    "errors": {
        "Accept-Language": [
            "The PreferredLanguages field is required."
        ]
    }
}
```
The same error occurs even when there is only one parameter attributes with `[FromBody]`.

A similar example with two ´[FromBody]` attributes has been posted in a swashbuckle issue:
https://github.com/domaindrivendev/Swashbuckle.AspNetCore/issues/2315
The dotnet version was net6.0 and it apparently worked there. Did something change for NET 7?

The example from https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/mvc/models/model-binding?view=aspnetcore-7.0#sources also shows an example, with a `[FromQuery]` attribute in the Instructor class. but it doesn't work, as I explained above. See also: https://github.com/dotnet/AspNetCore.Docs/issues/29295

The only working solution that I found was to use a separate class for the body:
```
public record Artist
{
    public string? Name { get; init; }

    public string? StageName { get; init; }
}

public record ArtistRequest
{
    [FromBody]
    public Artist Artist { get; init; }

    [FromHeader(Name = "Accept-Language")]
    public List<string> PreferredLanguages { get; init; }

    [FromQuery]
    public string? SelectedLanguage { get; init; }
}
```
This requires two DTO classes. Is there any other working solution with just one flat class?



### Expected Behavior

**1. )** It is expected that the model binding works flawless with one class:
```
[Route("one-class")]
[HttpPost
public ActionResult<ArtistRequest> PostOneClass(ArtistRequest artistRequest)
{
    return Ok(artistRequest);
}

public record ArtistRequestFlat
{
    [FromPath]
    public guid Id { get; init; }

    [FromBody]
    public string? Name { get; init; }

    [FromBody]
    public string? StageName { get; init; }

    [FromBody]
    public date? Age{ get; init; }

    [FromHeader(Name = "Accept-Language")]
    public List<string> PreferredLanguages { get; init; }

    [FromQuery]
    public string? SelectedLanguage { get; init; }

    public IPAddress IpAddress  { get; init; } //from custom model binder factory
}
```
ApiExplorer should **honor the attributes in the class**!

**2.)** The current way to add `[FromQuery]' is unintuitive. More clear would be to have an attribute like `[FromMixedSources]`
```
`public ActionResult<ArtistRequest> PostOneClass([FromMixedSources] ArtistRequest artistRequest)`
```
**3.)** Even with the current solution to use '[FromQuery]' in the controller method the model should be bound correctly using a flat model class.

**4.)** If the method parameter has a `[From Body]` attribute or it is added by convention specific parameters should still be honored. The current behavior to treat all properties as `[From Body}` is documented, but completely unintuitive and not an expected behavior. More specific settings should have precedence over more general settings.

This should work and **all properties should be filled from the respective source**. If body parameters are read first the other parameters can be added without complications.

So if a `[FromBody]` is set, it should be used only for properties that don't have a attribute or are handled by a custom model binder.

```
[Route("one-class")]
[HttpPost
public ActionResult<ArtistRequest> PostOneClassFromQuery([FromBody] ArtistRequest artistRequest)
{
    return Ok(artistRequest);
}

public record ArtistRequestFlat
{
    [FromPath]
    public guid Id { get; init; }

    public string? Name { get; init; } //[FromBody]

    public string? StageName { get; init; } //[FromBody]

    public date? Age{ get; init; } //[FromBody]

    [FromHeader(Name = "Accept-Language")]
    public List<string> PreferredLanguages { get; init; }

    [FromQuery]
    public string? SelectedLanguage { get; init; }

    //if necessary [FromCustomBinder]
    public IPAddress IpAddress  { get; init; } //from custom model binder factory
}
**6.)** The ApiExplorer should provide corrrect information for Swashbuckle to create a correct SwaggerUI, which is not working right now either.
```



